#no_prelude
// Stdlib: Multi-Load-Case FEA
//
// Placeholder for the v0.3.x multi-load-case FEA module. Will eventually host
// the LoadCase and MultiCaseResult structure definitions plus convenience
// helpers (envelope_von_mises, worst_case, ...) — see PRD task #1
// (docs/prds/v0_3/structural-analysis-fea.md, "Multi-load-case FEA" section).
//
// This file is intentionally documentation-only for task #3006. The
// `envelope_max` / `envelope_min` builtins are name-dispatched in
// `crates/reify-stdlib/src/fea.rs` — no `.ri` registration is required for
// them to be callable. PRD task #1 will populate this file with structure
// defs and wire it into `crates/reify-compiler/src/stdlib_loader.rs`.
//
// v0.4 shell BC framework (PRD task T15 — decomposition step 15):
//
// The `PinnedSupport` constructor and the shell-aware `FixedSupport` contract
// are name-dispatched in `crates/reify-stdlib/src/supports.rs` — no `.ri`
// registration is required, following the same pattern as `envelope_max` /
// `envelope_min`. Neither constructor requires a `structure def` here.
//
// Runtime semantics enforced by solver task T8 (shell BC application):
//   - `FixedSupport` on a shell entity auto-clamps all 6 DOFs (3 translational
//     + 3 rotational).
//   - `PinnedSupport` is the explicit-pin opt-out: constrains translational DOFs
//     only, leaving rotational DOFs free.
//   - `PinnedSupport` on a tet entity is semantically equivalent to
//     `FixedSupport` on tet; T8 emits a diagnostic warning in that case.
//
// See `docs/prds/v0_4/structural-analysis-shells.md` § "BC framework" for the
// full design rationale.
//
// v0.4 shell stress framework (PRD task T16 — decomposition step 16):
//
// `ElasticResult` (in `std/solver/elastic`) now carries six field-typed slots
// for shell-result data. Three of these are grouped into a companion structure,
// `ShellStress` (also in `std/solver/elastic`):
//
//   ElasticResult.stress  — kept as the legacy tet-compatible stress placeholder
//                           (Real, per TODO(field-in-param, task #3117)).
//   ElasticResult.frame   — new in T16: per-element local-to-global rotation
//                           (Real placeholder for Field<Point3<Length>,
//                           Matrix<3,3,Real>>). Set to Value::Undef for tet
//                           results; populated from the MITC3+ mid-surface
//                           mesher for shell results.
//   ShellStress.top       — top-surface Cauchy stress layer (Real placeholder
//                           for Field<Point3<Length>, Tensor<2,3,Pressure>>).
//   ShellStress.mid       — mid-surface (neutral-plane) stress layer. For tet
//                           results all three ShellStress channels are equal.
//   ShellStress.bottom    — bottom-surface stress layer.
//
// Runtime structured-stress contract (NOT implemented at the stdlib level):
// The backward-compatible alias `result.stress` → `result.stress.mid` for
// tet-to-shell migration, and the `to_global(stress, frame)` helper for
// transforming shell-local stress to the global Cartesian frame, are
// engine-integration concerns deferred to tasks T18-T20 ("Auto-classification
// dispatch", "Shell extraction failure handling", "Persistent-naming for
// derived mid-surface entities"). At the stdlib level T16 only declares the
// shapes; the alias and dispatch semantics are wired by the engine tasks.
//
// Rust runtime container: `crates/reify-solver-elastic/src/shell_result.rs`
// houses the `ShellStress` struct with a `homogeneous(field)` constructor for
// tet results (sets top == mid == bottom == field; frame = Value::Undef).
// Engine-integration tasks T18-T20 call `homogeneous` for tet elements and
// use direct struct initialisation for shell elements.
//
// See `docs/prds/v0_4/structural-analysis-shells.md` § "Stress through
// thickness" for the full design rationale.
